[1] Southern Russia - Volgograd
Date: Fri, 31 Mar 2006
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: Mosnews.com, 30 Mar 2006 [edited]
<http://www.mosnews.com/news/2006/03/30/vlgbirdflu.shtml>

The H5N1 strain of bird flu virus has been found in dozens of dead birds in
Russia's southern province of Volgograd, officials in the province told
AFP. "Today the provincial veterinary laboratory confirmed the presence of
the H5N1 virus in the blood of dead birds" found at a farmyard at the
village of Vesyoly, a statement from the Volgograd provincial
administration said.
Preventive work including disinfection is being carried out and 2 million
doses of bird flu vaccine have been sent to the province from Moscow, the
statement said.
Russia's chief veterinarian warned last week that bird flu was posing a
growing threat to the country. "In 2005 the virus affected 62 towns in 10
Russian regions, while since the start of 2006, already 56 towns in nine
regions have been affected," Sergei Dankvert said at a veterinarians'
conference.
The outbreak in Volgograd follows outbreaks in several other parts of
southern Russia as well as in nearby Turkey, Azerbaijan and Georgia.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Volgograd region (Oblast) is situated within Russia's Southern Federal
District (Yuzhny federalny okrug). For Russia's administrative division,
see 20050908.2666. For map, see
<http://www.grida.no/graphics/CEE/russia/russieoblast.jpg>. Volgograd is No
23 in the map. - Mod.AS]
